    "type": "ContextOfUse",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment. Operating conditions evaluated: blood temperature 37 °C ± 1 °C, inlet pressure range 5–15 mmHg, volumetric flow rates 2–8 L/min across five discrete set-points, rotational speeds 2400–3600 RPM, fluid viscosity 0.0035 Pa·s (non-Newtonian Carreau model), turbulent flow regime with Reynolds numbers 4000–12000 at pump inlet, and outlet back-pressure 80–120 mmHg representing physiological afterload. Hemolysis index evaluated against absolute clinical threshold of 0.1 g/100 L. These ranges are described in the prose rationale but are not formally encoded as a machine-readable operating envelope or applicability constraint.",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "decisionConsequence": "High"
  },
